    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-11-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-11-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> papers,
                        <persName>Whitman</persName> file</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum for the President, Prepared in the United States
                        Atomic Energy Commission</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d119fn1">The source text is unsigned but was prepared on
                            <gloss target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss> stationery. It was initialed “D.E.”
                        by President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWERGADD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-11-10">November 10,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The atomic energy relationships between the United States and Canada, if they
                    come up during your visit,<note n="2" xml:id="d119fn2">The President visited
                        Canada Nov. 13–14. No record of discussions on atomic energy has been
                        found.</note> should be currently benefited as we will be informing the
                    Canadians today of the arrangement for more extensive technical cooperation
                    under the <hi rend="italic">Modus Vivendi.</hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d119fn3">They <hi rend="italic">Modus Vivendi</hi> is
                        recorded in the minutes of the Combined Policy Committee, Jan. 7, 1948; for
                        text, see <ref target="frus1948v01p2#pg_679">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1948, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, Part 2, p. 679</ref>.</note> This will give
                    them information on effects of atomic weapons to assist them in defense
                    preparations.</p>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Suggested points that might be made if occasion arises:</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Express appreciation of the American people for the Canadian contribution
                        to the common defense effort by the production and sale of uranium to the
                        United States—stressing particularly the sympathetic and understanding
                        cooperation of <persName>C.D. Howe</persName>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Express hope that continued vigorous search for uranium will result in
                        greater production.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>State that you have directed the Chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission
                        to recommend amendments to the Atomic Energy Act at next session of Congress
                        to provide for broader cooperation with Canada and friendly nations.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
